data.title: Office of Public Information News Releases
data.meta_description: Korean War Educator is a joint effort of civilians and veterans who are determined to establish and maintain a medium in which the general public can learn more about the Korean War.
data.text:
Introduction

Throughout the war years, the Department of Defense's Office of Public Information in Washington, D.C. distributed official news releases detailing the U.S. casualties in the Korean War. These releases were sent to newspapers and other media throughout the United States. Following are some of those news releases and the text found within them. These particular releases were sent to the Decatur Herald and Review newspaper and thus are associated mostly with Illinois Korean War casualties, with a smattering of information about other states. The scribbles on some of the pages are notes made by H&R staff members.

These important documents were rescued from imminent destruction in Decatur, Illinois by a veteran who understood their historic significance. The KWE does not know the name of the rescuer to give him a round of applause for his outstanding preservation efforts, but the documents came to light in an exhibit about the Korean War held in the Douglas County Museum in Tuscola, Illinois in the mid-1990s. The material was submitted for the exhibit by a member of the Charles Parlier Chapter (Decatur, Illinois) of the Korean War Veterans Association.

What makes these documents so important? Not only do they list the Killed and Missing in Action, they also list the names of veterans who were injured in the Korean theatre of action (a rare find) and those who were returned to duty after an injury was healed. These dated, government-issued documents can be used as evidence in disability claims. Furthermore, government workers trying to locate next of kin for DNA testing can obtain leads from the documents since they list next of kin and their addresses. They also provide the branch of service that the veteran served in during the Korean War, as well as the serviceman's rank at the time of injury or death.

The Korean War Educator is interested in hearing from any reader who has a similar group of documents for other states. Contact Lynnita.
